                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3b27qh58/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>are not assailed, and their religious privilege in no way molested”? I<lb/> replied,\n                sustaining my position, and declared at the conclusion that<lb/> I should no farther\n                notice any “<hi rend=\"underline\">anonymous</hi>” communication. Yet, “A Jew”<lb/>\n                again came forth, defending the treaty, repeating the charge of my ignorance,<lb/>\n                and calling all that had as yet been written on the subject by<lb/> Editors “flimsy\n                remarks.” In reply to him, <persName>Mr. J. N. Cardoza</persName><lb/> entered the\n                arena in a most gentlemanly and quiet Article.<lb/> To this “A Jew” replied in a\n                most scurrilous and insulting<lb/> Article, without even once coming to the point at\n                issue, nay! he was<lb/> even so ungenerous &amp; uncharitable, not to say\n                ungentlemanly, to cast<lb/> some open flings at me, although I had withdrawn from\n                the controversy<lb/> and thus placed myself beyond the possibility of\n                    <sic>defence</sic>.</p>\n            <p>Now <persName>Mr. N.</persName> published an Article, containing a most\n                withering<lb/> lesson for the unavoidable position which “A Jew” had taken in this\n                affair.<lb/> The latter took <sic>offence</sic> at this and published a card,\n                demanding<lb/> an explanation from <persName>Mr. C.</persName> This was not given,\n                and so there<lb/> was for the last 3 days a fine prospect of a duel. Things,<lb/>\n                however, I think, are now settled. You yourself were drawn<lb/> into this\n                controversy. In his first Article, <persName>Mr. C.</persName> quoted from<lb/> the\n                Occident, Vol. XII, p. 95-100, to prove that you had then already<lb/> written\n                against the Treaty <hi rend=\"underline\">as it now stands</hi>; “A Jew” denied<lb/>\n                this fact, in his reply, maintaining that you meant the original draft<lb/>\n                containing the word “<hi rend=\"underline\">Christian</hi>,” and to prove this, he quoted<lb/>\n                <hi rend=\"underline\">from Vol. 15, <date>March '51</date></hi>!!! Is this not very\n                fair, after <persName>Mr C.</persName> had<lb/> quoted your very words and which\n                could certainly not be found in the<lb/>\n                <date>March</date> Number of <date>1851</date>!? What must “A Jew” now think of<lb/>\n                this incidental point, after having read your Article on the<lb/> Swiss Treaty, in\n                which you refer to the very pages quoted<lb/> by <persName>Mr. C.</persName>? Has\n                your usual informant or reporter not com-</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3b27qh58/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
